<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-multiplying-matrices-i" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Multiplying Matrices I</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.7 Matrices I
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title> 
                    <p>
                        Multiply compatible matrices in different situations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <!-- [LP] Add guidance on activity -->

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To provide an rationale for the formula for matrix multiplication formula and introduce it through a practical example.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p> We continue with Kelvin and Esther from <xref ref="mango-shopping"/>. As a reminder, this matrix represents their purchases of mangoes, oranges, and banans from the shop in Soy:
            <me>
                \mathbf{S} = \begin{bmatrix}  5 &amp; 2 &amp; 1 \\ 6 &amp; 1 &amp; 3 \end{bmatrix}
            </me>
            The first column tells us that Kelvin bought 5 mangoes and Esther bought 6 mangoes.
            </p>    
            <ol marker="1.">
                <li>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If mangoes cost Ksh 10 each, oranges cost Ksh 15 each, and bananas cost Ksh 5 each, how much does Kelvin spend at the shop in total?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Kelvin spends <m>5 \times 10 + 2 \times 15 + 1 \times 5 = \text{Ksh } 85</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>  Help Learners break this up by fruit if they are struggling
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            What about Esther?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Esther spends <m>6 \times 10 + 1 \times 15 + 3 \times 5 = \text{Ksh } 90</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Could you write the costs as a matrix? What shape might it take?
                        </p>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                            Learners might write the costs as a <m>1\times3</m> matrix, like so: <me>\mathbf{C} = \begin{bmatrix} 10 &amp; 15 &amp; 5 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Or they might write the costs as a <m>3\times1</m> matrix, like so: <me>\mathbf{C} = \begin{bmatrix} 10 \\ 15 \\ 5 \end{bmatrix}</me>.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Encourage both representations, and show Learners a different option if they only provide one. Foreshadow that the second representation will be more useful for the next part of the question.
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                Learners should not have units (like Ksh) in their matrix, but understand that these entries represent quantities of money.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If mangoes cost Ksh <m>x</m>, oranges cost Ksh <m>y</m>, and bananas cost Ksh <m>z</m>, can you create an expression for how much Kelvin spends?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Kelvin spends <m>5 \times x + 2 \times y + 1 \times z</m>. 
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Suppose that, next week, prices have increased from 1(a), so that mangoes cost Ksh 12 each, oranges cost Ksh 20 each, and bananas cost Ksh 8 each. 
                    </p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Can you find how much Kelvin and Esther would spend next week?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    Kelvin spends <m>5 \times 12 + 2 \times 20 + 1 \times 8 = \text{Ksh } 108</m>, and Esther spends <m>6 \times 12 + 1 \times 20 + 3 \times 8 = \text{Ksh } 116</m>.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Can you represent your answers from 1(a) and 2(a) in a <m>2\times2</m> matrix, with a row for Kelvin and Esther, and column 1 representing the total cost this week and column 2 representing total cost next week.
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                     <me>\begin{bmatrix} 85 &amp; 108 \\ 90 &amp; 116 \end{bmatrix}</me>. The first column represents the total cost this week, and the second column represents the total cost next week. 
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                            <note component="lesson-plan">
                                <p> If students have the transpose of this matrix (with Kelvin and Esther as columns), encourage them to write it the other way (since this preserves the rows for Kelvin and Esther). </p>
                            </note>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Could you generalise your result? What if this week mangoes cost Ksh <m>x</m>, oranges cost Ksh <m>y</m>, and bananas cost Ksh <m>z</m>, and next week mangoes cost Ksh <m>a</m>, oranges cost Ksh <m>b</m>, and bananas cost Ksh <m>c</m>? What would the matrix look like then?
                            </p>
                            <solution component="lesson-plan">
                                <p>
                                    <me>\begin{bmatrix} 5x + 2y + z &amp; 5a + 2b + c \\ 6x + y + 3z &amp; 6a + b + 3c \end{bmatrix}</me> The first column represents the total cost this week, and the second column represents the total cost next week.
                                </p>
                            </solution>
                            <note component="lesson-plan">
                                <p> If students struggle to get this abstraction, break it up step by step (e.g. Kelvin's total cost in the first week, then second week etc.) </p>
                            </note>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>

